faq:
  - q: "Do I need a cover letter?"
    a: "For roles you genuinely want, yes — if the application accepts one. Most applicants skip optional cover letters, which means submitting one puts you in the top 20% of applicants automatically. A strong cover letter can tip a borderline application forward. A weak one is worse than none. For high-volume tech roles at large companies, cover letters are rarely read by the first screener — but for senior roles, leadership positions, and any role requiring writing skill, they matter significantly."
  - q: "How long should a cover letter be?"
    a: "Three to four short paragraphs — 250 to 400 words. Anything longer is not a cover letter; it is a second resume. Recruiters spend 6–10 seconds on a cover letter. Every sentence must earn its place. Shorter and more specific is always better than longer and more comprehensive."
  - q: "What should a cover letter include?"
    a: "Paragraph 1: Who you are, your current level, and a specific reason you are interested in this company or role — not generic flattery. Paragraph 2: The single most relevant thing about your background for this role — one story or outcome with a number. Paragraph 3: Why this specific company and role fits your direction. Closing: A clear, confident call to action — you are available for a conversation. No 'I hope to hear from you.'"
  - q: "What is the biggest cover letter mistake?"
    a: "Summarizing your resume in paragraph form. A cover letter that just restates what is already on your resume adds zero information and wastes the reader's time. The cover letter's job is to add context your resume cannot — your specific interest in this company, the one story that makes you the obvious candidate, and a signal that you have done real research."
  - q: "Should I address the hiring manager by name?"
    a: "Yes, if you can find the name. Check LinkedIn, the company website, and the job posting. 'Dear [Name]' is always better than 'Dear Hiring Manager' or 'To Whom It May Concern.' If you genuinely cannot find the name, 'Dear Hiring Team' is acceptable. 'To Whom It May Concern' signals zero effort."
  - q: "How do I write a cover letter for a role I am underqualified for?"
    a: "Lead with the strongest transferable experience you have — the thing that most directly maps to what they need. Acknowledge the gap if it is obvious, but do not dwell on it. Then pivot to why your trajectory and adjacent experience makes you a compelling bet. The best underqualified cover letters make the reader feel the risk of not interviewing you is higher than the risk of the gap."
howto:
  name: "How to Write a Cover Letter"
  steps:
    - name: "Open with a specific hook — not your name"
      text: "Do not start with 'My name is [Name] and I am applying for...' — the recruiter can see your name on the application. Instead, open with a specific observation about the company, a direct statement of your most relevant credential, or a compelling question. Make the first sentence earn attention."
    - name: "Paragraph 1 — Who you are and why this company"
      text: "Establish your current role and level in one sentence. Then name one specific thing about this company — a product decision, engineering approach, recent announcement, or mission element — that is genuinely interesting to you. This proves you researched beyond the careers page."
    - name: "Paragraph 2 — Your single most relevant story"
      text: "Pick the one achievement from your background that most directly maps to what this role needs. Tell it in 3–4 sentences with a specific outcome. This is your proof point — the reason they should believe you can do the job."
    - name: "Paragraph 3 — Why this role fits your direction"
      text: "Explain how this role connects to what you are trying to accomplish next. Be specific — not 'I want to grow' but 'I want to own platform direction for a product-led company, which this role offers in a way my current role does not.' This shows intent and reduces the perceived flight risk."
    - name: "Close with confidence, not hope"
      text: "End with a direct, confident call to action. 'I would welcome a conversation — I am available [time frame].' Not: 'I hope to hear from you' or 'Thank you for your consideration.' Confident language signals a candidate who knows their value."
